    detailedExplanationExpert: `The framing effect here exploits reference-dependent preference construction. The positive frame (learn from industry experts) activates gain-focused processing while the negative reality (one guest lecture per semester) would activate loss-focused processing. This cognitive bias is a cornerstone of behavioral economics, showing that rational choice theory's assumption of frame-independent preferences is empirically violated.`,
