    detailedExplanationExpert: `Named after medieval fortifications, the Motte-and-Bailey fallacy exploits the ambiguity between a modest defensible claim ('with enough effort, most people can significantly improve their abilities') and an ambitious unsupported claim ('you can be anything you want'). When the bailey is contested, the arguer retreats to the motte, then later re-asserts the bailey as if it were established. This rhetorical strategy conflates distinct propositions and evades proper scrutiny of the stronger claim.`,
